data.sampled: The name of the option strategy being implemented is a long put butterfly. This strategy consists of purchasing two options with a lower strike price and selling two options with a higher strike price, all with the same expiration date. The purpose of the long put butterfly is to profit when the stock price settles near the middle strike price at expiration, which in this case is $42. The net credit received from the sale of the options with a higher strike price offsets the cost of the lower strike price options, reducing the overall cost of the strategy.

This strategy involves buying a put option with a higher strike price and selling a put option with a lower strike price, both with the same expiration date. The goal is to benefit from the difference between the premiums received from selling the lower strike price put and premiums paid for the higher strike price put. data.sampled: This is a trading strategy known as a Long Straddle. In this strategy, a trader purchases an equal number of out-of-the-money puts and calls on the same underlying asset and expiration date. The purpose of this strategy is to profit from a volatile price movement in either direction, while limiting the potential loss to the initial premium paid for the options. The long straddle is popular during times of high market volatility or when the traders expect a significant price movement, but they are not sure in which direction the price will move. The profit is realized if the price of the underlying asset moves significantly in either direction away from the current market price.

The name of the overall option strategy being implemented is a Box Spread or a Credit Spread, which is a combination of a bull put spread and a bear call spread. The investor is looking to profit from a narrow trading range of the underlying stock between the sold $93 put and bought $110 call strikes, while also benefiting from the difference in premiums between the purchased $90 put and sold $105 call options. If the stock price stays within the specified range at expiration, the investor pockets the difference in premiums without exercising any options, resulting in a net credit received at the outset of the trade.
